<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="162" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[140,1108,448,827]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">
<bibRefCitation author="Majka CG &amp; Klimaszewski J" box="[185,558,554,580]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="48 - 72" refId="ref10650" refString="Majka CG, Klimaszewski J (2008) Introduced Staphylinidae (Coleoptera) in the Maritime Provinces of Canada. Th e Canadian Entomologist 140: 48 - 72." type="journal article" year="2008">Majka and Klimaszewski (2008)</bibRefCitation>
removed this species from the New Brunswick faunal list, based on a misidentified specimen reported in 
<bibRefCitation author="Majka CG &amp; Ogden J" box="[805,1103,589,616]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="761 - 764" refId="ref10680" refString="Majka CG, Ogden J (2006) Brachygluta abdominalis (Aube) newly recorded in Canada (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae) with notes on other beach-drift beetles. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 108 (4): 761 - 764." type="journal article" year="2006">Majka and Ogden (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. However, the above records of R.P. Webster establish the presence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donisthorpe" authorityYear="1935" box="[919,1077,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptacinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedius">
<emphasis box="[919,1077,624,650]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">L. intermedius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the province (
<figureCitation box="[291,357,659,686]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[141,175,1590,1612]" captionTargetBox="[140,1108,790,1564]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[140,1108,790,1564]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 5. Distribution of Cilea silphoides, Atheta dadopora, Leptacinus intermedius, Bisnius cephalotes, Neobisnius villosulus, Philonthus jurgans, Anotylus tetracarinatus, and Anotylus insecatus in the Maritime Provinces of Canada." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3769604" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3769604/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Consequently, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Donisthorpe" authorityYear="1935" box="[544,699,659,685]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptacinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedius">
<emphasis box="[544,699,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">L. intermedius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reinstated to the faunal list of New Brunswick. Th e earliest North American specimens are from 
<quantity box="[816,903,694,721]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.83362" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" unit="in" value="1903.0">1903 in</quantity>
Québec (
<bibRefCitation author="Smetana A" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 389" refId="ref11280" refString="Smetana A (1982) Revision of the subfamily Xantholininae of America north of Mexico (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada 120: i-iv + 1 - 389." type="journal article" year="1982">Smetana 1982</bibRefCitation>
). Widely distributed in Europe and found in North Africa and 
<collectingCountry box="[918,996,730,756]" name="Turkey" pageId="11" pageNumber="162">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Herman LH" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 4218" refId="ref9869" refString="Herman LH (2001) Catalogue of the Staphylinidae (Insecta: Coleoptera): 1758 to the end of the Second Millennium. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 265: 1 - 4218." type="journal article" year="2001">Herman 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Smetana A" box="[212,391,765,792]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="624 - 698" refId="ref11397" refString="Smetana A (2004 b) Subfamily Staphylininae Latreille, 1802: In: Lobl I, Smetana A (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Vol. 2. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 624 - 698." type="book chapter" year="2004">Smetana 2004b</bibRefCitation>
), it has been recorded in a wide variety of decompositional environments including dung, compost, and decaying vegetable matter (
<bibRefCitation author="Smetana A" box="[901,1067,800,826]" pageId="11" pageNumber="162" pagination="1 - 389" refId="ref11280" refString="Smetana A (1982) Revision of the subfamily Xantholininae of America north of Mexico (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada 120: i-iv + 1 - 389." type="journal article" year="1982">Smetana 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
